About the Data Set

Reason

The primary reason that I chose this climate data set is because Shenzhen is my hometown back in China and I lived there for nearly 20 years. Upon my own experience in Shenzhen, sometimes weather, temperature and humidity are so unpredictable, so I am curious about whether I could find some correlations between each weather parameters or at least cram out some visualizations of it. And it was an incident that I found this website from the link from the final project pdf that it actually show every single years climate for Shenzhen from 1957 to 2017.

Description

This data set contains 15 climate attributions as well as day on 670 individual days from January 2016 to end of the October 2017 from Shenzhen, a tropical area and economic special zone in China.

Variable Description

Variables Definition
Aver_temp Average temperature (\(^\circ\)C)
Max_temp Maximum temperature (\(^\circ\)C)
Min_temp Minimum temperature (\(^\circ\)C)
Atom_press_sea Atmospheric pressure at sea level (hPa)
Aver_hum Average relative humidity (%)
Total_rain_or_snow Total rainfall and / or snow melt (mm)
Aver_vis Average visibility (Km)
Aver_windsp Average wind speed (Km/h)
Max_sus_windsp Maximum sustained wind speed (Km/h)
Max_windsp Maximum speed of wind (Km/h)
Rain_or_dizz Indicate whether there was rain or drizzle (In the monthly average, the total days it rained)
Snow indicate if it snowed (In the monthly average, the total days it snowed)
Storm Indicate whether there storm (In the monthly average, Total days with thunderstorm)
Fog Indicate whether there was fog (In the monthly average, Total days with fog)

Raw Data

  • Correlations Between certain variables?

  • When the humidity would Change?

Combine the data from 2016 to 2017/10 in Shenzhen to one whole year data set

#Combine this 2016 and 2017 climate data for each month into one whole year data set------
Weather_ShenZhen <-
  Jan %>%
  full_join(Feb) %>%
  full_join(Mar) %>%
  full_join(Apr) %>%
  full_join(May) %>%
  full_join(June) %>%
  full_join(July) %>%
  full_join(Aug) %>%
  full_join(Sep) %>%
  full_join(Oct) %>%
  full_join(Nov) %>%
  full_join(Dec) %>%
  full_join(Jan1) %>%
  full_join(Feb1) %>%
  full_join(Mar1) %>%
  full_join(Apr1) %>%
  full_join(May1) %>%
  full_join(June1) %>%
  full_join(July1) %>%
  full_join(Aug1) %>%
  full_join(Sep1) %>%
  full_join(Oct1)


#Revise the names for the data set to its reality names------
Weather_ShenZhen <-
  Weather_ShenZhen %>%
  mutate(Date = seq(as.Date("2016/1/1"), as.Date("2017/10/31"), by = "day")) %>%
  rename(Aver_temp = "T", Max_temp = "TM", Min_temp = "Tm", Atom_press_sea = "SLP", Aver_hum = "H", Total_rain_or_snow = "PP", Aver_vis = "VV", Aver_windsp = "V", Max_sus_windsp = "VM", Max_windsp = "VG", Rain_or_driz = "RA", Snow = "SN", Storm = "TS", Fog = "FG")

Weather_ShenZhen = Weather_ShenZhen[,-c(1)]

Write out the data set so that we could work on it easily without revising it

write.csv(Weather_ShenZhen, "~/Desktop/STAT184/Final Project/Weather_ShenZhen.csv")

1. Fundamental Exploratory Analysis

Firstly, we want to know the average temperature during these two year period. And show the specific date that the temperature would exceed this average with the count of it

#Calculate out the mean value of the temperature during the date range 
Weather %>%
  mutate(num_Aver_temp = tidyr::extract_numeric(Aver_temp)) %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  summarise(Aver_temp_two = sum(num_Aver_temp)/nrow(Weather))
##   Aver_temp_two
## 1      23.99806
#Use the threhold(i.e. mean temperature = 23.99806 calculated from the previous part) to show the specific date that the temperature would exceed this average
Spec_date <-
  Weather %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  filter(readr::parse_number(Aver_temp) > 23.99806) %>%
  select(Date,Aver_temp)

#inspect the first few date with temperature greater than the average temperature during the two-year-period
head(Spec_date)
##         Date Aver_temp
## 1 2016-04-06      24.3
## 2 2016-04-07      25.2
## 3 2016-04-08      24.9
## 4 2016-04-09      24.7
## 5 2016-04-14      24.4
## 6 2016-04-16      25.7
#show the count of the dates that have the greater temperature than the average
nrow(Spec_date)
## [1] 390

Conclusion:

The average temperature during the period from January 2016 to October 2017 is around \(23.998^\circ\)C and there are 390 days that have greater temperature than the average during this period in Shenzhen.

Secondly, we want to know the most frequent weather conditons in Shenzhen

Weather %>%
  filter(Storm == "o") %>%
  summarise(count_storm = sum(n()))
##   count_storm
## 1          82
Weather %>%
  filter(Fog == "o") %>%
  summarise(count_fog = sum(n()))
##   count_fog
## 1        13
Weather %>%
  filter(Rain_or_driz == "o") %>%
  summarise(count_rain = sum(n()))
##   count_rain
## 1        320

Conclusion:

From above report, we could conclude that the most frequent weather conditions is rain or drizzle in Shenzhen.

Thirdly, we want to know whether the change of temperature during each day would be different under different weather conditions

One way to do that is by creating a variable with different levels indicating specific weather conditions and create a boxplot to compare the mean and varability of each

#First we will need to create a factor variable with different levels indicating specifical weather condition
Weather <-
  Weather %>%
  mutate(Conditions = 
           ifelse(Rain_or_driz == "o"&Storm == "o"&Fog == "o",
                  "Rain_or_driz & Storm &Fog", 
                  ifelse(Rain_or_driz == "o"& Fog == "o",
                         "Rain_or_driz & Fog",
                         ifelse(Rain_or_driz == "o"&Storm == "o",
                                "Rain_or_driz & Storm",
                                ifelse(Rain_or_driz == "o", 
                                       "Rain_or_driz",
                                       ifelse(Storm == "o",
                                              "Storm",
                                              ifelse(Fog == "o",
                                                     "Fog","Sunny")))))))

#inspect the data set

#Now,create the boxplot for each possible weather conditions
Weather %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  mutate(diff = tidyr::extract_numeric(Max_temp)-tidyr::extract_numeric(Min_temp)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Conditions, y = diff)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  xlab("Weather Conditions") +
  ylab(expression(paste("Temperature Change (",degree~C,")")))

Observations:

From the boxplot of any possible weather conditions

  • The change of temperature during each day would be mostly different under the condition of any possible weather conditions in Shenzhen, except between raining or drizzle and the mixture of raining or drizzle & Fog (since they have close mean).

  • In addition, since the average temperature change under raining or drizzle and mixture of raining or drizzle & Fog are nearly the same, we could also say that Fog would have relatively small influence on the change of temperature in Shenzhen.

Another way to do this part is by creating a variable with 2 levels: single weather and mixture of weather

#We could then create an factor variables with 2 levels with single weather & mixture of weather based on the conditions variable we just created
Weather <-
  Weather %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  mutate(Single_Mix = 
           ifelse(Conditions == "Storm",
                  "Single Weather",
                  ifelse(Conditions ==grep("^[R][^&-]*$",Conditions, value = TRUE),
                         "Single Weather",
                         ifelse(Conditions == grep("^[Fog]",Conditions, value = TRUE),
                                "Single Weather",
                                ifelse(Conditions == grep("Sunny", Conditions, value = TRUE),
                                       "Single Weather",
                                       "Mixture of Weather")))))

Lastly, we want to know whether numbers of occurance for different weather conditons would change for certain period

#We want to transform each month from number to abbreviation of month for further use
Weather[14] <- as.Date(Weather$Date)
month <- month(ymd(Weather$Date))

#Build the function that transform each month from number to abbreviation of month
month_to_abb<-
  function(month)
    {
    month<-
      ifelse(month == "1","Jan",
        ifelse(month == "2","Feb",
              ifelse(month == "3","Mar",
                     ifelse(month == "4","Apr",
                            ifelse(month == "5","May",
                                   ifelse(month == "6","Jun",
                                          ifelse(month == "7","Jul",
                                                 ifelse(month == "8","Aug",
                                                        ifelse(month == "9","Sep",
                                                               ifelse(month == "10","Oct",
                                                                      ifelse(month == "11","Nov",
                                                                             "Dec")))))))))))
    month = factor(month, levels = month.abb)
  }

#Together
Weather %>%
  mutate(month = month(ymd(Weather$Date)))%>%
  ggplot(aes(x = month_to_abb(month))) +
  geom_bar(aes(color=Conditions,fill=Conditions),alpha=0.5) +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=60,hjust=1,size=16),axis.text.y=element_text(size=16),axis.title=element_text(size=16,face="bold"))+
  xlab("Month")

#Seperate (facet with conditions and single_mix)
Weather %>%
  mutate(month = month(ymd(Weather$Date)))%>%
  ggplot(aes(x = month_to_abb(month)))+
  geom_bar() +
  facet_grid(Single_Mix~Conditions) +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=60,hjust=1,size=16),axis.text.y=element_text(size=16),axis.title=element_text(size=16,face="bold")) +
  xlab("Month")

#Single and mixture of weather count
Weather %>%
  mutate(month = month(ymd(Weather$Date)))%>%
  ggplot(aes(x = month_to_abb(month)))+
  geom_bar() +
  facet_wrap(~Single_Mix) +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=60,hjust=1,size=16),axis.text.y=element_text(size=16),axis.title=element_text(size=16,face="bold"))+
  xlab("Month")

Observations:

  1. From the first plot,
  • We could see Fog would only happens for February, March and May in Shenzhen.
  1. From the second plot,
  • We could see occurrence of Sunny weather dominate all other weather conditions in Shenzhen.
  • In additions, Rainging or drizzle started to decline from October to December and the highest numbers of Rainging or drizzle happened normally at January. These make sense since period between October to December is in Winter and the weather is started to get dry and it seldom rains or drizzle in Shenzhen and during January, the start of Spring in Shenzhen, lots of rain here upon my own experience.
  • All three Weather conditions except for Sunny happen a lot on July and it make sense since it is one of the typical features that a tropical area should have when it comes to Summer, where heavy Rain, fog and storm should be expected.
  1. From the third plot,
  • We could conclude that Shenzhen is a city with greater numbers of mixture weather than single weather during the whole year.

2. Correlations between Certain Variables?

Part 1

In this part, we want to investigate whether there is correlation between Average temperature and Atmospheric pressure at sea level in the area of Shenzhen taking into considerations of any possible weather conditions

Weather$Atom_press_sea <- readr::parse_number(Weather$Atom_press_sea)
Weather$Aver_temp <- readr::parse_number(Weather$Aver_temp)

Weather %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Aver_temp,y=Atom_press_sea)) +
  geom_point(aes(shape = Single_Mix)) +
  facet_wrap( ~ Conditions) +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=60,hjust=1,size=16),axis.text.y=element_text(size=16),axis.title=element_text(size=16,face="bold"))+
  xlab(expression(paste("Average Temperature (",degree~C,")")))+
  ylab("Average Pressure at sea level (hPa)")

Observations:

Based on the graphs provided above, we could conclude that there is a seemly negative correlation between the average temperature and the atmosphere pressure at the sea level in Shenzhen under any possible weather conditions. (i.e.as the average temperature increase, the atmosphere pressure at the sea level would possibly decrease in the region in Shenzhen)

Part 2

Next, as many people may have concerned that there was always a rumor saying that the change of temperature would have a hugly impact on the average relative humidity from which the effects would show significances in many tropical area like Shenzhen. Thus, in this part we want to test the validity of this statement

#In this part, we first define the change in temperature and next we omit the NA and then we create a plot frame and plot with difference of the temperture V.S. the average relative humidity to see the relationship.
Weather %>%
  mutate(diff = tidyr::extract_numeric(Max_temp)-tidyr::extract_numeric(Min_temp)) %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=diff,y=Aver_hum)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=60,hjust=1),axis.title=element_text(face="bold"))+
  xlab(expression(paste("Temperature Change (",degree~C,")"))) +
  ylab("Average Relative Humidity(%)")

Conclusion:

According to the Temperature Change V.S. Average relative humidity plot, we could conclude that the change of temperature would indeed have a hugely impact on the humidity, however, in a negative way. (i.e.as the change of the temperature increase, the average relative humidity would decrease correspondingly in Shenzhen)

3. When the humidity would Change?

#The general pattern during the two-year-peroid
Weather %>%
  mutate(dayof_year = lubridate::yday(Date)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = dayof_year,y=Aver_hum)) +
  geom_point() +
  xlab("Day of Year") +
  ylab("Average Relative Humidity(%)")

#To check whether the pattern is accurate, check the plot with the whole year
Weather %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Date,y=Aver_hum)) +
  geom_point() +
  xlab("Date") +
  ylab("Average Relative Humidity(%)")

#Check!(repeated within the same pattern)

Observations:

Generally, from the plot, we could see that in Shenzhen, the relative humidity would remain constantly high from Summer to the mid of Fall(100th to 250th day of year). And during the start and end of the year, the average humidity would remain unstable which could possibly caused by the rainy season or typhoon or any other factors.
